<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="78" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1087,1834]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1663,1689]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dai, Zhang &amp; Zhang" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[652,766,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Siniassus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aspinus">
<emphasis box="[652,666,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[680,766,1663,1688]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">aspinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished from the later by the pygofer with several macrosetae on caudo-dorsal margin and style narrowed gradually to apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="78" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1087,1834]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1735,1761]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species name is derived from the Latin prefix “nigri-” (black) and word “maculatus” (maculated), referring to the irregular black markings on the pronotum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
